ce:section.ce:para:
The feasibility of the designed ratiometric complex probe for the detection of Cu2+ was evaluated carefully by two certified reference materials (Table 2
                        ) and spiked real water samples (Table 3
                        ). The recovery experiment of Cu2+ was performed by using natural water samples, including tap water and river water (collected from Yellow River, Lanzhou). Tap water was tested here because it is of practical importance to detect Cu2+ rapidly. Both samples were first filtered through 0.45 μm filter membranes after collection. Cu2+ was spiked with different concentrations to evaluate the effect of sample matrix. As shown in both tables, the recoveries are in the range of 91.0–107.3% and the RSDs are all not higher than 5.4%, which are all consistent with the results by using standard method. Above results confirmed the usability of the complex probe for the detection of Cu2+ ions in real water samples.
